Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to "settle" in cities - chinanews.com
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
The natural ecology of the capital continues to improve, attracting wildlife cities to "settle"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
(Reporter Wang Bin) A reporter from Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscape and Greening Bureau that with the continuous improvement of the natural ecological environment in the capital in recent years, the species and number of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebral wild animals inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including first - class protected animals such as brown horse chickens and black storks, as well as second - class protected animals such as impala, whooper swans, gray cranes, and mandarin ducks.
Whether it is an urban forest planted in the Second Ring Road or a small wetland embedded between buildings, it not only brings wild nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In the middle of summer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by a mountain stream, while two dogs and badgers were joking with each other.
Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Management Office, said that by the end of 2019, 178 species of wild animals, including the national first - class protected animal golden eagle and the national second - class protected animal spoon chicken and impala, were living in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, and that nearly one - third of the city's wild animal species could be found here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real'owners', and our staff can only be considered'bodyguards' at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the reserve on the ground, more than 30 professional rangers patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and once a month, they also make a "big circle", which takes them to almost the entire reserve in a full day.
"During the inspection, it is necessary not only to check and record biodiversity, but also to check and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install infrared cameras in the wild, and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli said that with the increasing biodiversity of protected areas in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera, leopards, raccoons, and badgers have become "resident guests", and the "appearance rate" of the national second - class protected animal impala has also become higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, Director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Department of the Beijing Landscape and Greening Bureau, said that the number of terrestrial vertebral wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 species today, and that the species and number of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The presence of wild animals in cities is becoming more and more common, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of the greening of the capital city in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening of one million mu, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of woodland and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature".
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green areas to facilitate wild animals to "visit relatives and friends", and the trees planted are also honey and food source plants that animals love.
I am dedicated to helping computers communicate with the world around us.
