Polish Justice Minister Jobro held a press conference and said that his Ministry of Justice would make a request to the Ministry of Labor and Family to begin withdrawing from the treaty on Monday.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
"The treaty contains elements that we think are harmful in the form of meaning," Gioblo said.
Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party and its coalition partners have a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and promote a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Andrzej Duda made hostility to gay rights one of the main issues during his successful re - election campaign this month.
On Friday, thousands of Poles, most of them women, protested against the withdrawal from the convention in Warsaw and other cities.
Lempat, one of the organizers of the protest, said at a protest march in Warsaw, "The purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legalize domestic violence."
