The United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic airliners registered in the United States, because corrosion of the air check valves of these airliners could cause the engines to stop in the air.
The FAA said it has received four reports of engine parking in the air for 737NG and 737Classic airliners so far, so it has made an emergency inspection request for airliners that have been parked continuously for 7 days or more, and airliners that have flown less than 11 times so far since they were put back into flight.
The FAA warned that if the level 5 check valves of all two engines of the airliner were corroded, they could become stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and be unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace the key component before the airliner is put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the new coronavirus outbreak had reduced travel demand, and as a result, many airliners were mothballed or used less, making "check valves more susceptible to corrosion."
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the airliners involved in the directive, and that if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that the airliners of major U.S. airline operators usually fly multiple times in a day, but after the outbreak of the new coronavirus, a large number of airliners were grounded; with the recent slow growth in passenger travel demand, some airliners have returned to service.
The FAA did not release details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its airliners was en route from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled, and the airliner finally made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the jet's engine and had inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines, and Southwest Airlines respectively said on the 24th that their airliners did not experience engine stall related to the air check valve.
Four American Airlines airliners will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines airliners will be inspected.
Delta said it would inspect 20 of its airliners, but did not say whether there had been any engine stalls.
Several media reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive was another blow to Boeing.
Indonesian Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines each crashed a Boeing 737MAX in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of airliners was subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year, and resumed production in May.
Steve Dixon, the head of the FAA, admitted in June that the FAA had "made a mistake" in its regulation of Boeing with regard to the 737MAX.
