Hoh Xili Tibetan Antelope Enters Remigration Season - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Hoh Xili Management Office of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Management Director that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelopes that had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Hoh Xili to give birth were ending their calves and beginning to return to their original habitat with their calves.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three young Tibetan antelopes through the 3002 km of the Qinghai - Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge of the Qinghai - Tibet Railway, and the Tibetan antelopes have begun to move back.
Experts have analyzed that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope calves in relocating sheep has accounted for one - quarter to one - fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope sheep.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said, "At the beginning of the migration, Tibetan antelopes face a high risk of predation, so the number of calves in the herd will be relatively small, and there may even be no calves."
According to statistics from the Hoh Xili Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, Director of Management of Sanjiangyuan National Park, the overall number of Tibetan antelopes returning has been increasing year by year, and the number of Tibetan antelopes returning in 2019 was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said, "It is expected that the return migration of Tibetan antelopes will end in early September this year, and the number of returning Tibetan antelopes is expected to continue to increase."
The Tibetan antelope is a national first - class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, Aljinshan in Xinjiang, and other places go to Zhuonai Lake, located in the hinterland of Hoh Xili, to lamb.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on the protection of Tibetan antelopes in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said, "The return migration of Tibetan antelopes is the process of female Tibetan antelopes returning to their habitat with their calves after they have given birth. At first, the return migration group that left the calving site is relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
To ensure the safe return of Tibetan antelope sheep, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xili Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, the director of management of Sanjiangyuan National Park, has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main return areas.
If a Tibetan antelope sheep is found trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to allow the sheep to pass safely through the wildlife passage and ensure that they are as little disturbed by humans as possible on their way back.
So, how should we relieve the heat in our daily life?
Experts suggest that when going out in summer, try to avoid hot periods, and it is best not to walk or work in the blazing sun around noon, because the sun is strongest in this time period, and the possibility of heatstroke is higher.
If you must go out at this time, you must do a good job of protection, such as wearing a parasol, a visor, and sunglasses, and if you have conditions, it is best to apply sunscreen to prevent sunburn.
Try to choose cotton, hemp, and silk textures with light colors and good breathability, and wear less chemical fiber clothing, so as not to dissipate heat in time when sweating a lot, which can cause heatstroke.
In hot and sultry weather, prepare enough water to drink, drink it in time, and do not wait for thirst to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water, so limit your water consumption to 150 ml to 200 ml at a time, and drink warm water, not ice water.
Depending on the temperature, the average person drinks 1.5 liters to 2 liters of water per day, and the high - temperature worker drinks 3 liters to 5 liters of water per day.
When sweating more, some salt water can be properly replenished to make up for the salt lost by sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to potassium deficiency in summer, which makes people feel tired and tired, and potassium - containing tea is an excellent summer drink.
In summer, eat fruits and vegetables with high water content, such as lettuce, cucumbers, tomatoes, etc.; fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons, etc., with a water content of 80% to 90%, can be used to replenish water; dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people working in high - temperature environments should properly supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium, and other elements.
In summer, the days are long and the nights are short, the temperature is high, the metabolism of the human body is strong, the consumption is also large, and it is easy to feel tired.
Adequate sleep can relax all systems of the brain and body, which is not only beneficial to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heatstroke.
Experts say the best bedtime is from 22:00 to 23:00, and the best time to get up is from 5:30 to 6:30.
When sleeping, be careful not to lie under air conditioning vents and electric fans, so as not to suffer from air conditioning diseases and hot colds.
Experts suggest that people who are engaged in outdoor activities or high - temperature work should carry heat prevention drugs such as 10 drops of water, Rendan, patchouli water, or patchouli pills with them, or place them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent heatstroke.
