APEC Trade Ministers Say They Will Accelerate Regional Economic Recovery - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) - A video conference of trade ministers of Asia - Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) members was held on July 25, and the meeting pledged to work to reduce the impact of the new coronavirus outbreak on the regional economy and accelerate the realization of a resilient, sustainable, and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was chaired by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting said that the trade ministers of APEC members recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non - discriminatory, transparent, and predictable trade and investment environment to promote economic recovery at this challenging time.
All parties pledged to ensure that the emergency measures taken to deal with the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent, and temporary, that they do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, and that they abide by the rules of the World Trade Organization.
In the statement, the trade ministers of APEC members pledged to strengthen cooperation to promote the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening supply chain flexibility, and minimize disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food, and agricultural products in order to cope with the epidemic.
The trade ministers of APEC members agreed on the need to discuss ways to reduce non - tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential goods, and reiterated their commitment to promote the necessary cross - border movement of people without affecting the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The meeting also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of necessary commodities.
The declaration states that all economies will ensure that their trade measures in response to the epidemic comply with WTO regulations, and commit to take action to reduce non - tariff trade barriers and promote trade in order to promote the flow of goods necessary under the epidemic.
