France increases military investment in space - Xinhuanet
French Defense Minister Florence Parly said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to its space defense budget and develop military forces in space to prevent "unfriendly moves" that other countries may make in outer space.
Parly told La Provence on the same day that between 2019 and 2025, France's budget for military space projects will increase from 3.6 billion euros ($4.2 billion) previously proposed to 4.3 billion euros ($5 billion).
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019 - 2025, which was approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation satellites and communications satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites, and improve the modernization of its space surveillance radar.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced in July last year that a space military command and an "aviation and space force" would be established within the French Air Force.
Parly said she will officially announce the establishment of the space force when she visits a military academy in Salon - en - Provence later.
Parly said that the space force belongs to the Air Force and will have a strength of 500 personnel by 2025.
She said, "In the past, people thought that space served the common interests of science, but this idea is gone forever. Today, space is a place where countries compete for global hegemony."
Parly reiterated Macron's previous statement, saying that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race, but it is my responsibility to fully recognize the threats we may face."
Parly revisited the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said that it was a Russian satellite that was "peeping".
The Russian side denies this claim.
Parly said that France will "soon" have small patrol satellites that can detect and target "those behind unfriendly moves".
French media believe that France sought to establish a space force because US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense to draft a bill to establish the Pacific Air Force in February last year.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act in December last year, approving the establishment of the Pacific Air Force, the sixth military branch of the United States.
Some experts fear that these measures by the US have accelerated the militarization of space in the US and may lead to a new arms race in space.
