The report says the shared accommodation market has picked up since March - chinanews.com
(Reporter Yang Zhaokui) The China Shared Accommodation Development Report 2020 (hereinafter referred to as the Report) recently released by the Sharing Economy Research Center of the National Information Center shows that due to the impact of the epidemic, the transaction value of China's shared accommodation market fell by 72.1% year - on - year in the first five months of 2020.
However, the shared accommodation market began to pick up in March, and the market turnover, order volume, and number of people received gradually recovered.
The report shows that the transaction value of the shared accommodation market has fallen sharply, on the one hand, due to the sharp decline in the demand for travel accommodation under epidemic prevention and control, and the sharp decrease in the number of orders, with the total number of orders falling by 65% year - on - year in the first five months and the number of visitors falling by 63% year - on - year; on the other hand, the weak demand has also led to a significant decline in overnight prices, with the average overnight price falling by 16% year - on - year in the first five months.
However, in March, April, and May, the market turnover increased by 78%, 199%, and 35% respectively; the number of orders increased by 141%, 152%, and 50% respectively; and the number of visitors increased by 81%, 112%, and 28% respectively.
The report points out that the development of the shared accommodation industry has been promising for a long time, but there are still many uncertainties in the near future.
In this regard, Yu Fengxia, deputy director of the Sharing Economy Research Center of the National Information Center, told the Worker's Daily reporter that the development of shared accommodation needs stronger policy support, and on the one hand, it is necessary to do a good job in implementing policies already introduced in the early stages, further strengthen policy publicity, and pay attention to creating a better business environment; on the other hand, it is also necessary to further strengthen policy guidance and support in terms of stimulating consumer demand, enriching the supply of tourism and accommodation services, innovating service methods, and strengthening cooperation between the government and platform enterprises.
