chinanews.com, Xiamen, July 26 (Yang Fushan Zhang Shushan Xu Jingyi) - The vascular surgery department of Shanghai Changhai Hospital of the Naval Medical University, a well - known vascular surgery center in China, signed a contract with the vascular surgery department of Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University here on July 25 to jointly set up a collaboration center to promote exchanges and cooperation between the two sides in the field of vascular surgery, especially in the field of acute and severe aorta.
Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University said that after the vascular surgery departments of the two hospitals officially formed a collaborative unit, they will conduct remote consultations, conduct real - time online consultations with Changhai Hospital to formulate treatment plans, select talents for further training, and jointly carry out weekly surgical technical exchanges, teaching rounds, and so on; for complex cases, Changhai experts can be invited to the hospital to perform surgery according to the needs of patients, so that patients in southwest Fujian can enjoy the top medical resources in China without leaving the province.
The two hospitals will also work together to carry out innovative surgical research, popular science and early screening of aortic diseases, and so on.
A special seminar on aorta hosted by the Beijing Health Promotion Association and hosted by Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University was held in Xiamen on the same day.
The two well - known hospitals in Shanghai and Xiamen held the signing ceremony of the Vascular Surgery Collaboration Center at the same time at the meeting, and announced the formation of a collaborative unit to jointly improve the treatment level of vascular surgery - related diseases in southwest Fujian.
The vascular surgery department of Shanghai Changhai Hospital is the only research institute of vascular surgery in the army and the only clinical medical center for vascular system diseases in Shanghai, as well as the first national key discipline of vascular surgery, and has led the establishment of the professional committee of endovascular science of the Chinese Medical Association, which is a top team with deep experience in the industry.
Professor Huang Xiaojin, Director of Vascular Surgery at Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University, gave an interview to the media.
Vascular surgery at Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University is the first vascular surgery established by an independent discipline in Fujian Province, and has been committed to the diagnosis and treatment of aortic and peripheral vascular diseases for a long time, and was approved to build a provincial - level clinical key specialty in 2018.
In the treatment of aortic diseases, in addition to the treatment of dissecting aneurysms and aortic aneurysms, he has extensive experience in the treatment of emergency ruptured aortic aneurysms.
"Vascular surgery at Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University is outstanding in the region in terms of its history of development, the breadth, difficulty, and complexity of surgery, so this time we set up a collaboration center to carry out in - depth medical, teaching, and scientific research cooperation in the diagnosis and treatment of lower extremity arteries, carotid arteries, and other diseases, in addition to aorta."
Professor Feng Rui, deputy director of vascular surgery at Shanghai Changhai Hospital, said.
Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Xiamen University and Shanghai Changhai Hospital signed a contract to establish the "Li Zhaoshen Famous Medical Studio" in gastroenterology in 2018.
Professor Huang Xiaojin, the director of the vascular surgery department of the hospital, said in an interview with CNNMoney that the vascular surgery department of the hospital has also had a long history of exchanges with Changhai Hospital, and that the two hospitals officially formed a collaborative unit this time, bringing the cooperation and exchange between the two sides to a new level.
He said that the hospital will regularly invite Shanghai experts to Xiamen to carry out surgical technical exchanges, teaching rounds, and discussion of difficult cases, and at the same time further carry out remote consultations, and currently plans to conduct remote consultations once a week; in addition, the department will also send personnel for further training and exchange to strengthen the training and development of the subject talent team.
The reporter learned at the meeting that vascular disease is the number one cause of death in China, and that the aorta, as the main artery of various organs of the human body, flows from the heart to the whole body, and plays an important role.
The occurrence of aortic disease is often accompanied by high risk, high mortality, and difficult treatment; the thickest section of the aorta is 4 cm in diameter, and once a hemangioma is formed, a rupture occurs, or the lining of the blood vessel ruptures, resulting in a dissection, it will cause haemorrhage, which is very dangerous.
In recent years, as people's lifestyles have changed and the pace of life has accelerated, China has become the world's largest country for high blood pressure, and aortic diseases have also increased, and today, with the development of surgical techniques and industrial materials, the treatment of aortic diseases continues to develop in the direction of minimally invasive, rapid, and efficient treatment.
Doctors can properly "channel" the blood flow by piercing the thigh and placing a stent in the aorta, thereby avoiding the impact of aneurysms or ruptured dissections and achieving good treatment results, and some surgeries even require local anesthesia.
More than 10 domestic experts were invited to the symposium to discuss new advances in the treatment of aortic diseases, and to conduct cutting - edge technical training and discussion of difficult cases in the form of conference salons.
The reporter learned at the meeting that with the development of surgical technology and industrial materials, the current treatment of aortic diseases continues to develop in the direction of minimally invasive, rapid, and efficient treatment.
