Is it reasonable for a 3 - year - old child to sue the university after being smashed playing in the college playground?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the child was compensated before suing the school
This is not the case, but it is the case that this is the case.
Three - year - old Xiao Wen was playing in a college playground when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen compensated, Xiao Wen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiao Wen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding an apology from the school where the playground was located, as well as payment of medical expenses and compensation for emotional damage totaling 20,000 yuan.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, that it had fulfilled its proper safety and security obligations, and that Chen had made compensation, and dismissed the plaintiff's claim accordingly.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiao Wen to play in the school playground while the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid this risk, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen, and many other children and parents moved in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, Chen Mou, a member of the softball team, lost his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the net into the above - mentioned safe area and hit Xiao Wen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiao Wen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believed that the facilities of the school stadium did not meet the relevant safety regulations, and that the team and related facilities were not effectively managed.
The school's negligence led to the above - mentioned incident, which caused Xiao Wen great physical and mental pain, as well as great pain to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that entering the playground must maintain a safe distance from the training ground and reminding them to pay attention to their own safety, and that the plaintiffs could not prove that the school "failed to fulfill its safety and security obligations", so they did not agree to compensation.
After the trial, the court held that the site of the incident was a site open to the public free of charge by the university involved, and that although the school had safety and security obligations for the management of the playground, such safety and security obligations only needed to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and had fulfilled its proper safety and security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiao Wen for medical expenses, transportation expenses, and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the compensation agreement previously reached, and the two parties agreed to resolve the dispute at one time.
Afterwards, Xiao Wen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, but there was no legal basis, and the court dismissed all of the plaintiffs' claims.
After the verdict, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, bear the obligation of safety and security; if the actions of a third party cause damage to others, the third party bears the liability of tort, while the managers of public places who fail to fulfill the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that since, as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place, foresee possible dangers and damage, and thus is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or mitigate the extent of damage, and that the cost of avoiding and mitigating the occurrence of damage is the lowest, the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, the safety and security obligations of the school should be compatible with the social activities of non - specific entrants in the playground, which is open to the public free of charge, and specifically, the school should take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform about hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third - party infringement, even if managers of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their safety and security obligations, their liability is a supplement to compensation for damages, and according to the newly promulgated Civil Code, managers can also recover compensation from third parties after assuming supplementary liability.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victims should not expand the scope of their claims after they have received compensation from the direct infringer.
