Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
At the beginning of the new coronavirus outbreak, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed new coronavirus cases in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of the new coronavirus was confirmed in Israel itself, and Israel quickly adopted measures such as closing all entry and exit ports, suspending non - essential industries, switching schools to online classes, restricting public transportation and non - essential social activities, sealing off cities severely affected by the epidemic, and jointly maintaining prevention and control measures by military police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results, and by mid - May, the number of confirmed new coronavirus cases in a single day in Israel had fallen to single digits.
With the epidemic under control and all prevention and control measures in Israel fully unsealed, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially since the beginning of July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the number of new daily cases in Israel has been above 1,500 for eight days, and by the time of writing on July 25, the number of new cases on that day had reached 916.
As of July 25, there have been 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
Faced with the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs, and other public entertainment venues, and at the same time introduced a policy to restrict public transportation, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of the "city closure" on weekends, and stipulated that the "city closure" would be implemented from 17:00 on Fridays to 5:00 on Sundays.
During this period, people can go out, but places such as shops, shopping malls, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools, and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people will be prohibited on all dates and time periods, gyms, studios, and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes will not be allowed to eat, and only takeaway services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to join forces with the government in the fight against the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest and march because the government's prevention and control measures affected their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti - epidemic policies affect the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's ban on restaurants, cafes, and other prevention and control measures without corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people did not abide by the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when outdoors, and to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wore masks on their chins or hung them on their wrists.
During the epidemic, the school was the hardest hit area for the spread of the new coronavirus, and according to a recent visit by a reporter to the kindergarten here, the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the expert advisory group on the fight against the epidemic of the National Security Council of Israel, believes that Israel is moving towards a "dangerous situation", and points out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and that all leisure and entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks a master plan to fight the epidemic, and that the Knesset and various government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on the issue of fighting the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictions in different departments.
